problem: Find the projection of the vector $\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$ onto the vector $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix}.$
solution:
From the formula for a projection,
\[\operatorname{proj}_{\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}} \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix} = \frac{\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix}}{\left\| \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix} \right\|^2} \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix} = \frac{6}{13} \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix} = \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 12/13 \\ -18/13 \end{pmatrix}}.\]
model_solution:
## Step 1: Identify the vectors for projection
The vector to be projected, \(\vec{a}\), is \(\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}\) and the vector onto which the projection is made, \(\vec{b}\), is \(\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix}\).

## Step 2: Calculate the magnitude squared of vector \(\vec{b}\)
The magnitude squared of vector \(\vec{b}\) is given by \(\left\| \vec{b} \right\|^2 = b_1^2 + b_2^2 = 2^2 + (-3)^2 = 4 + 9 = 13\).

## Step 3: Calculate the dot product of vectors \(\vec{a}\) and \(\vec{b}\)
The dot product of vectors \(\vec{a}\) and \(\vec{b}\) is given by \(\vec{a}\cdot\vec{b} = a_1b_1 + a_2b_2 = (3)(2) + (0)(-3)
## Step 4: Calculate the projection of vector \(\vec{a}\) onto vector \(\vec{b}\)
\(\text{proj}_{\vec{b}}\vec{a} = \left( \frac{\vec{a}\cdot\vec{b}}{\left\| \vec{b} \right\|^2} \right) \vec{b} = \left( \frac{6}{13} \right) \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 12/13 \\ -18/13 \end{pmatrix}\)
